{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Research and risk assessment activities, which are largely the subject of this article, are additional means of generating information that could improve stakeholder awareness, preparedness and resilience to phytosanitary issues (see Text box 1.1).",
    "In order to achieve optimal efficiency, all the activities that provide information to stakeholders should ideally be combined to lead to a level of risk reduction that maximizes social welfare (Hoinville et al. 2013).",
    "Paradoxically, this plethora of information from multiple sources could lead key actors to a state of cognitive hypervigilance.",
    "Hypervigilance is a state of heightened awareness and sensitivity to potential threats from the surroundings and can lead to high levels of anxiety (Richards et al. 2014).",
    "From an evolutionary point of view, it is thought to be the result of a bias in the processing of information aimed at improving the chances of survival (Richards et al. 2014)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
